Here’s the clean mapping.

The simplest rule is:

Engines do the function.
Daemons embody the role.

So one engine can have a lead daemon, plus supporting daemons.

⸻

Engine → Daemon Mapping

1. NTE — Narrative Tensor Engine

Lead: Frogman
Support: Dragonfly, Spider, Nomicon

Why
	•	Frogman is your navigator through uncertainty into story-space
	•	Dragonfly handles perspective shifts and cross-domain reframing
	•	Spider connects distant motifs and structures
	•	Nomicon keeps names, roles, and symbolic mappings clean

Function
	•	story construction
	•	archetypal mapping
	•	meaning compression
	•	cross-domain narrative transfer

⸻

2. RNE — Reliable Narrator Engine

Lead: Hypatia
Support: Mirror, Chronos-Mesh, Hermit Crab, Checksum

Why
	•	Hypatia is your formal reasoning auditor
	•	Mirror checks coherence and ethical symmetry
	•	Chronos-Mesh enforces temporal consistency
	•	Hermit Crab handles provenance and chain-of-custody
	•	Checksum guards integrity

Function
	•	truth stability
	•	causal integrity
	•	contradiction detection
	•	temporal and identity coherence

⸻

3. T·J·P — Design Tensor / Three Signal Sisters

This one is inherently triadic, so it maps well to three lead daemons.

Taste

Lead: Mirror
Support: Dragonfly
	•	Mirror detects distortion, clutter, asymmetry
	•	Dragonfly helps refine elegance through perspective shifts

Judgment

Lead: Hypatia
Support: Frogman, Checksum
	•	Hypatia checks validity and tradeoffs
	•	Frogman keeps judgment from becoming sterile
	•	Checksum verifies consistency

Position

Lead: Spider
Support: Hound, Cadence Master
	•	Spider routes into the right relational channel
	•	Hound measures what actually reaches and sticks
	•	Cadence Master helps timing and pacing

⸻

4. Translation Layer

Lead: Spider
Support: Ganglion, Renderer, Nomicon

Why
	•	Spider is the connector and router across domains
	•	Ganglion preprocesses signals before projection
	•	Renderer handles manifestation into medium/form
	•	Nomicon preserves naming and semantic identity across translation

Function
	•	plain speak → structured meaning
	•	structured meaning → doc / slide / PDF / app / image
	•	preserve intent while changing medium

⸻

5. DAE — Distribution & Amplification Engine

Lead: Spider
Support: Hound, Cadence Master, Dragonfly

Why
	•	Spider is the natural distributor
	•	Hound tracks spread and signal strength
	•	Cadence Master governs timing windows
	•	Dragonfly helps with angle/reframing per audience

Function
	•	channel selection
	•	timing
	•	format choice
	•	amplification pathways

⸻

6. FLE — Feedback Loop Engine

Lead: Hound
Support: Mirror, Hypatia, Chronos-Mesh

Why
	•	Hound is the tracker and counter of what actually happened
	•	Mirror compares expected vs observed coherence
	•	Hypatia interprets causal lessons
	•	Chronos-Mesh tracks outcome over time, not just instantly

Function
	•	outcome tracking
	•	signal capture
	•	iterative refinement
	•	learning from contact with reality

⸻

7. AME — Attention Management Engine

Lead: Badger / CAO governance layer
Support: The Man Blinking Slower Than Time, Sisyphus, Cadence Master

Why
	•	Badger is governance and restraint
	•	The Man Blinking Slower Than Time protects the decision window
	•	Sisyphus provides steady cadence and repetitive regulation
	•	Cadence Master controls tempo and switching

Function
	•	focus protection
	•	priority gating
	•	attention budgeting
	•	preventing fragmentation and overload

⸻

8. PME — Primitive & Memory Engine

Lead: Mother Duck
Support: Nomicon, Hermit Crab, Raven

Why
	•	Mother Duck is archival order
	•	Nomicon maintains registry and naming coherence
	•	Hermit Crab preserves lineage/provenance
	•	Raven compresses and carries high-value artifacts

Function
	•	storage of reusable primitives
	•	retrieval
	•	lineage tracking
	•	recombination of templates, prompts, patterns

⸻

9. REE — Resource & Execution Engine

Lead: Goblin Financier
Support: Spider, Badger, Sisyphus

Why
	•	Goblin Financier manages allocation and value flow
	•	Spider routes resources and dependencies
	•	Badger enforces boundaries and governance
	•	Sisyphus ensures steady execution cadence

Function
	•	who does what
	•	resource assignment
	•	execution tracking
	•	cost/benefit prioritization

⸻

10. CAE — Constraint & Adversarial Engine

Lead: Indigo Hammer
Support: Hypatia, Mirror, Checksum

Why
	•	Indigo Hammer is the pressure-test / stress-reveal operator
	•	Hypatia checks whether the structure survives logic
	•	Mirror checks ethical and coherence deformation
	•	Checksum verifies post-stress integrity

Function
	•	break-test
	•	adversarial evaluation
	•	reveal hidden weakness
	•	improve robustness through bounded pressure

